04108nam a22006375i 9780814785133DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147851337 a10.18574/97808147851332doi  a(DE-B1597)548294  a(OCoLC)194285819  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX8777.6.A4 D35 2007 7aREL0790002bisacsh04a289.941 aDallam, Marie W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDaddy Grace :bA Celebrity Preacher and His House of Prayer /cMarie W. Dallam. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource :b12 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Race, and Ethnicity ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Call of God Brought Him -- t2. The Usual Miracles -- t3. Led by a Convicted Man -- t4. He Ousted God from Heaven -- t5. My Joy Is Completed in Charlotte -- t6. Chaotic Confusion -- tConclusion -- tAn Essay on Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCharles Manuel "Sweet Daddy" Grace founded the United House of Prayer for All People in Wareham, Massachusetts, in 1919. This charismatic church has been regarded as one of the most extreme Pentecostal sects in the country. In addition to attention-getting maneuvers such as wearing purple suits with glitzy jewelry, purchasing high profile real estate, and conducting baptisms in city streets with a fire hose, the flamboyant Grace reputedly accepted massive donations from his poverty-stricken followers and used the money to live lavishly. It was assumed by many that Grace was the charismatic glue that held his church together, and that once he was gone the institution would disintegrate. Instead, following his 1960 death there was a period of confusion, restructuring, and streamlining. Today the House of Prayer remains an active church with a national membership in the tens of thousands.Daddy Grace: A Celebrity Preacher and His House of Prayer seriously examines the religious nature of the House of Prayer, the dimensions of Grace's leadership strategies, and the connections between his often ostentatious acts and the intentional infrastructure of the House of Prayer. Furthermore, woven through the text are analyses of the race, class, and gender issues manifest in the House of Prayer structure under Grace's aegis.Marie W. Dallam here offers both a religious history of the House of Prayer as an institution and an intellectual history of its colorful and enigmatic leader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Pentecostal & Charismatic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785133.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK